{"/service/ndnp/nmu/batch_nmu_globemallow_ver01/data/sn92070582/00280774145/1921030701/0551.xml":{"full_text":"4\nTHE ALBUQUERQUE EVENING HERALD, ALBUQUERQUE, NEW MEXICO, MONDAY, MARCH 7, 1021\ni\nOH EVEN\nAFT\nTA\nTHE\nTHE things we buy every day-the necessities of life are\ndown to a standard. The great markets of the country\nare established to an extent unknown since before the war.\nThe merchant who sells you these necessities knows that the\nspring merchandise on his shelves is as low as it can be in price this season.\nHe knows because the manufacturers of these goods have already billed him for them. The\nmanufacturers in turn know that the prices of these things have reached the seasons bottom\nbecause they have purchased and paid for raw materials and labor that made them.\nLiving costs have come down in Albuquerque. Wage earners are still at work. This condi\ntion is ideal. It\ncan be continued.\nFollowing t h e\nsigning of the ar\nmistice prices\ncame down 10'\nBuyers waited\nthre e m onth s.\nThey expected\nfurther reduc\ntions. Some factories\nclosed down all\nretarded produc\ntion. Two million\nmen were thrown\nout of wnr!:.\nBuying had stop\nped but living\nwent on. Ncces-\nA Hundred Million People\nWill Read This Message\nrJ\"'HE substance of litis menage is deemed so important\nby men wlio know that it is being published in lb?\nnewspapers of four hundred and fifty cities of the United\nStates and Canada whose circulations total more than one\nhundred million readers.\nIt is not a ms.;ar;e from one class to another it is not\na message from se'lers to buyers it is not a message from\nmanufacturers to tellers. BUT IT IS A MESSAGE\nFROM YGU TO YOUR NEIGHBOR, and from him to\nhis neighbor.\nREAD IT!\nsity forced pur\nchases. Then con\nsumers rushed to\nbuy.\nThis movement\ncreated a sellers'\nmarket. Prices\nadvanced 40'\nover the reduced\nprices.\nWe are again\nconfronted with\nthe same condi\ntion. Things cost\n33 less than\nthey did six\nmonths ago. But\nwe won't be\ncaught as we\nwere following\nthe armistice.\nWE know that prices are generally down as far as they possibly can come down this season\nand we are buying wisely economically, as a healthy nation should buy. Another rush\nto replenish depleted stocks would mean another sellers' market. We are satisfied with\na buyers' market. We know that it means better goods, lower prices and a willingness to serve.\nYou can't get away from the eternal law of competition. Now that niying has resumed,\ncontinue to buy and you sell raw materials and make healthy employment. Stop and you cut\noff your market.\nNeed Anything Built Stow\nWe've Reached an Even Keel After a Tail Spin of\nprices. Let's Keep It Even.\nI. lie\nKi\nwants\nCI\nHO\nFrom\nMen Who Know\nW. P. G. HARDING, Governor of the\nFederal Reserve Board: \"The country has\nrecovered its normal state. We are not in\ndulging in the old idea of extravagance,\nliving beyond our means. Nor are we\ntroubled fo much as we were a few weeks\nago with the other extreme of over-pessimism,\nwhere people get down in the dumps\nand they cannot see daylight; cannot see\nany hope; see nothing but gloom and dark\nness, I say this in all candor: We are now\nlooking forward to a year of constructive\ndevelopment. I wart to say that intrin\nsically there is no comparison today with\nconditions a yc?r ago, when there was un\near iness and apprehension among the bet\ninformed over the badly expanded credit.\nBusiness is now rapidly reaching a new\nlevel and approaching n sound and sane\nbasis. We have a better banking situation.\nWe have passed the danger point. We\nhave a better understanding of condi-\ntf\nions.\nCHARLES H. MARKHAM, Chicago,\nPretjdert Illinois Central Railroad \"There\nis every indication that v shall enter\nshortly i:pon a period of increasing husi\nnefs activity in this country, following the\ndeprcfirion vhich resulted from what we\nhave com to designate the 'buyers'\nstrike.' Tin: revival should have a whole\nsome reaction upon every lire of busirer\nwhich is founded upon a real emonomic\nneed, as are the railways anil the lumber\ntrade. I believe the tide already is turn\ning, and that we fhall tee it continue to\nstrengthen durinr the next few weeks and\nmonths.\"\nELBERT H. GARY, New York, Chair\nman of Board, United States Steel Cor\nporation \"I am as hopeful and confident\nof the future as I have been at any time.\nConditions are no worse than many\nmonths ago. The wonder is that they have\nnot been much worse. Conditions have\nbeen abnormal and even the minds of\nthoughtful people were distorted. This,\nof course, was a result of tne terrible lime\nwe have passed through. We have lh\nspirit and dcterminAtion !o overcome all\nobstacles to the greatet success.\"\nCHARLES M. SCHWAB, New York,\nChairman of Board, Bethlehem Steel Cor\nporation: \"Out of the past business\ndepression has come a sounder basis for\nthe nation's activities and business will\ngo forward with a buoyancy and force we\nhave never known before, as a result of re\norganization. The whole world during\nthe last few years has been a spendthrift\nand a waster. It has spent a large part of\nits liquid wealth and has now come to a\nperiod where it can go forward only by\nenergy and effort of the most vigorous\nkind. The only business foundations\nwhich arc r u-e and steady arc erected unon\nthe rock of economy.\"\nof Alb\n\"J!\nle","height":"21492","width":"16064"}}
